post_text:
AHCS Families,



We are excited to offer an opportunity for you to purchase coverage for the Chromebook that your student will be checking out this year. This plan includes extensive coverage for your child's device at a great rate. In order to expedite coverage you can print and sign the attached document and send money with your student this week. Please send in a sealed envelope and have students give the envelope to their teacher. If your family qualifies for the free and reduced lunch program this insurance will be covered by the school. If this cost puts your family in financial hardship, please communicate with your child's principal. If insurance is not purchased you may be responsible to cover the cost of repair or replacement of the device. If you have questions please call the school or email admin@ahcspatriots.us.



Thank you,



Mr. Rose

Board Chair Special Address to AHCS Graduating Class of 2020.

The 10 Principals of Cowboy Ethics:
1. Live each day with courage.
2. Take pride in your work.
3. Always finish what you start.
4. Do what has to be done.
5. Be tough, but fair.
6. When you make a promise, keep it.
7. Ride for the brand.
8. Talk less, say more.
9. Remember that some things are not for sale.
10. Know where to draw the line.

#ahcs #graduation2020 #boardchair #debyinfanger #cowboyethics

We are so proud of Taylor Krohn for graduating a full year early!

Since I've known Taylor she has taken advanced courses. She is driven and dedicated to her education. All of her teachers report that she works very hard and produces very good work!

Taylor is honest, kind, and responsible. She has done a wonderful job working on the yearbook and is a huge asset to our school in general.

I want to wish Taylor Good Luck as she moves on to the next phase of her life!

post_text:
Loyalty and compassion are the first words that come to mind when I think of Sydney Farrell. These are also two attributes of a great leader, and she is indeed a great leader. With the opportunity of serving as Senior Class President, she has shown the capability of taking on those responsibilities and helping her classmates and friends accomplish many goals this year. Not only has she shown that initiative, but she has also accomplished that feat which truly helps a good leader stand out: She has led by example. Her classmates have been able to look up to her and see the benefits that hard work can achieve. Her loyalty to her classmates has not gone unnoticed and she truly cares about those she leads and befriends. She is able to use her humor and wit to reach anyone. It is with excitement that I wish her the best as she now moves into her next phase of life. I know she will succeed! It has been an honor and privilege to be both her teacher and her mentor! Good Luck Sydney!

-Mr. Palmer

post_text:
The first time you meet Lana Estrada, chances are she will be very quiet, shy, and reserved. However, behind that silence, there is an intelligence that will take this girl far. As I have had the chance to both teach and mentor Lana, I can tell that she is going to go on to perform extraordinary things in her lifetime. With her strong work ethic, she will accomplish anything to which she puts her mind and desire. One of her classmates describes her as motivated and discerning of her future. She is able to see how the goals she sets and achieves today will affect future life and outcomes. That discernment will be to her advantage as she begins her post-high school adventure. Good Luck Lana!

-Mr. Palmer

post_text:
Kaylee Dalton is graduating a full year early!

As I think about Kaylee as a student, a person, and what her future entails, there are many words that come to mind: funny, smart, capable, focused, and endearing. Kaylee is such an incredible student, and an even better human being. These words are attributes that will carry her to do great things. In today's world, so many are afraid to be themselves. They get stuck in comparison, locked into social media and seeing what others are, have become, and showcase, most of them being fake. Kaylee breaks that mold. She owns who she is and she doesn't look back. Due to this, Kaylee will create a future for herself that propels her farther than most. She has empathy for those who struggle and she is able to use that empathy to better herself. As we move forward as a school, we are truly proud to call Kaylee Dalton a graduate.

-Mr. Peterson

post_text:
Lucas Englert has made a great addition to our student body this year. He joined American Heritage as an exchange student from Germany. Lucas worked diligently at school in Germany and was able to graduate early. He decided to come to America as an exchange student to learn English and experience our culture, which he was already familiar with because of his love of movies, especially comedies. With patience and remarkable manners, Lucas quickly learned to communicate and thrive at our school, despite the language barrier. While Lucas attended American Heritage, he was able to experience the beautiful areas that surround Idaho Falls during the Hiking elective Mr. Palmer taught last fall. His spearmint gum is what got some of us through long and exhausting hikes. In his American Government and English classes, Lucas showed an incredible amount of patience and determination. Lucas has been a fantastic student and we wish him luck with his future endeavors.

-Mrs. Luker

It is crazy to think that when Ammon Brownlee first came to AHCS as a 9th grader, we didn‚Äôt think he would be with us for very long. His growth over the last 4 years has been amazing to watch. He has matured from a shy, unsure kid into a confident, intelligent, and outstanding young man. Ammon is truly a first-class act. He is smart, hardworking, kind, and helpful. He is the kind of student every teacher wishes to get at least once in his/her teaching career, and we at AHCS are sad to see him go. Ammon truly exemplifies what American Heritage Charter School is all about, and we hope we will continue to have students of his caliber as part of our graduating class each year! Good luck Ammon! Go forth and have the successful life you‚Äôre meant to have!

Mrs. Aycock

Idaho Falls Parks & Recreation
May 5 at 2:00 PM ¬∑

Join us for the 840 Get Out Challenge, and get a free prize!
The City of Idaho Falls Parks and Recreation Department and Safe Routes to School challenges you to be active for 30 minutes every day for 28 days. It‚Äôs called the 840 Get Out Challenge that starts Monday, May 11 and Ends Sunday, June 7. 840 represents the total activity minutes achieved if you accomplish the daily goal, every day. The City of Idaho Falls Parks and Recreation Department will be giving all individuals, who log 500 or more activity minutes, the official 840 Get Out Challenge sticker. Your activity minutes can be achieved by bicycling, long boarding, walking, jogging, or even doing the crab walk! Our goal is to inspire you to move a little more, whether on wheels or feet.
This challenge starts next Monday, May 11. For more information, check out the website page!
https://www.idahofallsidaho.gov/1516/840-Get-Out-Challenge

Your activity minutes can be achieved by bicycling, long boarding, walking, jogging, or even doing the crab walk! Our goal is to inspire you to move a little more, whether on wheels or feet.
This challenge starts next Monday, May 11. For more information, check out the website page!
https://www.idahofallsidaho.gov/1516/840-Get-Out-Challenge

shared_text:
LM Dalton
April 16 at 11:57 PM ¬∑

SOMETHING TO DO:

Chapter 1 - You Could Grow Your Own edible Sprouts. Buy or make your own sprouter and get cute seeds (alfafa, mung bean, clover, broccoli, radish for example) for edible sprouting. Sprouts are highly nutritious food and delicious in a salad or on a sandwich. If you carefully grow your own sprouts, you won't have to worry about getting sick or product recalls because of contamination. #knowwhereyourfoodcomesfrom Sprouter and seeds can be easily obtained on Amazon. Google "grow your own sprouts" for oodles of information and instructions.
Word of caution...Make sure you don't grow too many sprouts, or you will need to find some creative way to eat them. This may inadvertently create more work. For example: The excessive amount of mung bean sprouts that we made forced us to learn how to make Chinese food, a vegetable stir fry in order to use up the bean sprouts. It was delicious!
#STOPWHININGANDFINDSOMETHINGTODO

4-H Healthy Snack - Cowboy Caviar
Ingredients:
1- 15 oz. can kidney beans, drained
1- 15 oz. can black beans, drained
1- 15 oz. can diced tomatoes
1- 4 oz. can chopped green chilies
1- 15 oz. bag frozen corn, thawed
(or canned & drained)
¬º cup onion, finely chopped
3 limes, juiced
Salt and pepper to taste
Corn tortilla chips

Directions: Mix kidney beans, black beans, tomatoes, chilies, corn and onion in
large bowl. Add lime juice, salt and pepper; toss gently to combine.
Serve alone or with tortilla chips.
Servings: Makes 16 servings.

post_text:
Dear parents,

Thank you for your support as we adjust to social distancing as advised by the CDC. We are receiving great feedback from our AHCS families and we appreciate your efforts to help us continue your child‚Äôs education as best we can. Our teachers, our parents, and our students have had to make big adjustments as we follow our Cowboy Ethics principles!

As District 91 has now called off school until April 3rd, (and we share transportation) American Heritage will be doing the same. We have spring break starting tomorrow and going through next week. Then we will start up virtual classes again March 30th through April 3rd.

There is strong evidence that the virtual education for us could continue beyond that time but we hope things will improve and we can all get back to school!

Stay safe and stay in touch.
AHCS Board

Idaho State Department of Education
February 28 at 5:46 PM ¬∑

Explore NASA Internships! Internships are available from high school to graduate-level! One application is viewed agency-wide; interns are selected and placed in projects for fall, spring and summer at any NASA location! The deadline to apply for the summer session is March 8: https://intern.nasa.gov/

NASA internships and fellowships leverage NASA‚Äôs unique missions and programs to enhance and increase the capability, diversity and size of the nation‚Äôs future science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) workforce. Internships are available from high school to graduate level. Internships provide students with the opportunity to participate in either research or other experiential learning, under the guidance of a mentor at NASA.

Prior experience is not required and most interns receive a stipend award! Must be at least 16 years old at the time of application submission.

Idaho STEM Action Center
Idaho Science Teachers Association
NASA Idaho Space Grant Consortium

Idaho State Department of Education
February 19 at 11:09 PM ¬∑

Youth ages 15-18 should consider applying to participate in the Youth Conservation Corps, a summer employment opportunity available at national parks, forest, wildlife refuges, and fish hatcheries around the nation! A great opportunity nearby is the Kelly Forks Residential Youth Conservation Corps (northern Idaho) but apply NOW as the deadline is Feb 21: http://tiny.cc/2jr8jz

Or apply for the Yellowstone National Park YCC by March 1: https://www.nps.gov/yell/learn/management/yccjobs.htm

Participants are paid to accomplish needed conservation work on public lands and have the opportunity to work on historic structures, restore native species, disappearing trails, and the eradication of invasive species.

Find more opportunities through the National Park Service: https://www.nps.gov/subjects/youthprograms/ycc.htm

And through the US Forest Service: https://www.fs.usda.gov/working-with-us/opportunities-for-young-people/youth-conservation-corps-opportunities

This is a problem perpetuated by the educational elite. They, in their own self interest, have made it uncool to not go to college. Idaho State Department of Education
January 15 at 7:04 PM ¬∑

Call for high school student artists! The Western Governors' Association is now accepting submissions for the 2020 "Celebrate the West" regional art competition! Details: https://westgov.org/celebrate-the-west/competition/2020-competition

Entrants from WGA member states will create original two-dimensional artwork inspired by their state or informed by living in the West. Students may draw ideas from a variety of sources, including state history, landmarks, natural resources, National Parks and Monuments, people, communities, and culture.

Winning artists will receive cash prizes and their works will be displayed at an upcoming WGA Governors‚Äô meeting, as well as on the WGA website. Students must submit a digital copy of their entry via email by April 30, 2020! Governor Brad Little Idaho Commission on the Arts 6 On Your Side - Idaho
#Idaho #idedu #art

Youth Preparedness Camp 2020 | FEMA.gov

Idaho STEM Action Center
December 30, 2019 at 5:00 PM ¬∑

FEMA Region 10 is seeking forty (40) high-school aged youth representing Alaska, Idaho, Oregon, and Washington to attend a Youth Preparedness Camp near Anchorage, Alaska in July 2020. This will be an engaging and empowering way for teens to learn about and practice emergency preparedness.

FEMA will fund all participants‚Äô travel costs, including: lodging, meals, transportation to/from Ted Stevens Airport (ANC).

The deadline to apply is 11:59pm PST on January 19, 2020.
